subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Trunk completely segmented. Distal end of the cephalon straight (
Fig. 17 D
; 
Fig. 18 D
). Lateral processes, each with a tubercle on the dorsal surface. First pair separated from the second by more than its diameter. Second pair separated from the third by its own diameter. Third pair separated from the fourth by less than ½ its diameter (
Fig. 16
A–B; 
Fig. 17 D
; 
Fig. 18
D–E). Ocular tubercle conical (
Fig. 18 F
), located on the anterior cephalon, with four eyes, two anterior and two posteriors (
Fig. 16 B, D
; 
Fig. 17 B
). Abdomen vertical, inserted between the fourth pair of lateral processes (
Fig. 16 A
; 
Fig. 17 D
; 
Fig. 18 D, I
), (
Fig. 16 B
; 
Fig. 17 J
; 
Fig. 18 I
). Cylindrical proboscis with rounded anterior end, 3.5 times longer than wide, horizontal to body (
Fig. 16
A–B, D; 
Fig. 17 B
; 
Fig. 18
A–B). Triangular mouth, each lip lined with a dense fringe of setae (
Fig. 17 A
; 
18
A–B).

Chelifore three-articled, single-segmented scape, long, extends beyond the distal portion of the proboscis, with two dorsal setae and five distal setae (
Fig. 16
A–B, D, E; 
Fig. 17 B
). Chela well developed, without teeth, four middle setae on the ventral side of the movable finger, two mid-ventral setae on the immovable finger, one seta at the beginning of the immovable finger, two ventro-lateral setae on the base of immovable finger (
Fig. 16 E
; 
Fig. 17
B–C).

Thin legs. Coxa 1 with a dorso-distal seta. Coxa 2 widened distally (
Fig. 18 H
), with a ventro-distal long and pointed genital spur on both, male and female, on first and second legs genital spur are low and rounded, on third and fourth legs genital spurs are taller and conical (16 F, 18 G). Coxa 3 with four ventral setae, two ventro-distal setae and a middle-dorsal seta. Femur with a ventral row of six setae (five in the first half and one distal), three lateral setae; mid-dorsal tubular cement gland, and a dorso-distal projection with a long seta (
Fig. 17 F
). Tibiae 1 and 2 longest, subequal in length. Tibia 1, six times longer than coxa 1, with three lateral setae, three ventral setae, three proximal-dorsal setae, a mid-dorsal seta and two dorso-distal setae. Tibia 2, as long as tibia 1, in dorsal view with five small spines inserted proximally, one median and two distal setae, with a row of five ventral setae and a lateral one. Tarsus with two mid-ventral setae, a lateral seta and a thick ventro-distal seta. Propodus with a row of nine small dorsal spines and seven lateral spines in a row; heel with five thick setae; two rows of nine ventral sole spines directed towards the front (
Fig. 16
F–G; 
Fig. 17
E–G). Main claw ¾ propodus length, auxiliary claws minute (
Fig. 16 G
; 
Fig. 17 G
).
